INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9cb5bb7c-fc72-4378-8742-d3c3747990c3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$MLflow's Trinity — Reproducibility, Versioning, and Automation Done Right$escape$,
  $escape$MLflow's architecture directly encodes MLOps philosophy into its API surface. Reproducibility isn't aspirational — it's structural: every `mlflow.start_run()` captures a cryptographic `run_id`, and `mlflow.log_param()` / `mlflow.log_metric()` create an immutable audit trail tied to that run. Passing `run_id` to `mlflow.sklearn.load_model()` re-instantiates the exact artifact that was logged, down to the preprocessing pipeline.

Versioning is enforced through the Model Registry. Promoting a run's artifact via `MlflowClient.create_model_version()` creates an immutable version entry — you can never overwrite v3, only register v4. Stage transitions (`Staging → Production`) are explicit, logged state changes, not silent file overwrites.

Automation collapses via `mlflow.autolog()`: a single call before your training loop captures params, metrics, model weights, and the conda environment. Combined with MLflow Projects (`MLproject` manifest + entry points), you get hermetic, CLI-triggerable runs that reproduce on any machine with `mlflow run . -P alpha=0.1`. The payoff is debugging prod regressions by diffing two run IDs instead of asking "what did we train last Tuesday?"$escape$,
  $escape$import mlflow
from mlflow.tracking import MlflowClient

mlflow.set_tracking_uri("http://localhost:5000")
mlflow.set_experiment("churn-model")

mlflow.autolog()  # captures params, metrics, model, conda env

with mlflow.start_run() as run:
    model = train(X_train, y_train, alpha=0.1)
    run_id = run.info.run_id

client = MlflowClient()
mv = client.create_model_version(
    name="churn-classifier",
    source=f"runs:/{run_id}/model",
    run_id=run_id
)
client.transition_model_version_stage("churn-classifier", mv.version, "Staging")$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
