INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e52b253a-c6c6-4a1d-a450-cb8702231674',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$MLflow ONNX Flavor — Export, Log, and Serve Cross-Framework Models$escape$,
  $escape$MLflow's `onnx` flavor (`mlflow.onnx`) gives you a first-class way to log, version, and serve ONNX models alongside your experiment metadata. After converting a framework-specific model — scikit-learn via `skl2onnx`, PyTorch via `torch.onnx.export` — pass the resulting `ModelProto` directly to `mlflow.onnx.log_model()`. MLflow serializes the protobuf, writes an `MLmodel` manifest with the `onnx` flavor, and captures input/output signatures if you supply a `signature` argument.

At inference time, `mlflow.onnx.load_model(model_uri)` returns the raw `ModelProto`. Pass its serialized bytes to `onnxruntime.InferenceSession` for hardware-optimized execution with no framework dependency at serving time. Alternatively, wrap it with `mlflow.pyfunc.load_model()` to get a unified `.predict()` interface, useful when your serving layer is framework-agnostic.

One sharp edge: ONNX opset versions must align between exporter and runtime. MLflow does not validate this — a mismatch raises `InvalidGraph` at `InferenceSession` init, not at log time. Pin `opset_version` explicitly in your export step and record it with `mlflow.log_param` so it travels with the run.$escape$,
  $escape$import mlflow.onnx
import onnxruntime as rt
import numpy as np
from skl2onnx import convert_sklearn
from skl2onnx.common.data_types import FloatTensorType
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

clf = RandomForestClassifier().fit(X_train, y_train)
initial_type = [("float_input", FloatTensorType([None, X_train.shape[1]]))]
onnx_model = convert_sklearn(clf, initial_types=initial_type, target_opset=17)

with mlflow.start_run():
    mlflow.log_param("opset_version", 17)
    mlflow.onnx.log_model(onnx_model, artifact_path="onnx-model")
    run_id = mlflow.active_run().info.run_id

loaded = mlflow.onnx.load_model(f"runs:/{run_id}/onnx-model")
sess = rt.InferenceSession(loaded.SerializeToString())
preds = sess.run(None, {sess.get_inputs()[0].name: X_test.astype(np.float32)})[0]$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
